    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div type="letter">
                <div type="text">
                    <opener>
                        <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                        <date>May 3. 1877</date>
                        <salute>My dear Sir,</salute>
                    </opener>
                    <div type="transcription">
                        <p>Several years ago I should have been delighted to have undertaken the work which you propose, &amp; should have considered it a great honour; but I feel that I have not now strength sufficient in as much as the whole subject has to a large extent passed out of my mind. Whenever the results are published I shall look with especial interest to the account of the males of Scalpellum.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
                        <p>I beg leave to remain, my dear Sir | Yours very faithfully | Charles Darwin</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
            </div>
           
           
           <div type="footnotes">
                <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi> vol. 25, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10947.xml">letter from C. W. Thomson, 1 May 1877</ref>. For CD’s earlier reflections on Thomson’s discoveries with regard to males of the cirripede genus <hi rend="italic">Scalpellum</hi>, see <hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi> vol. 21, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9061.xml">letter to <hi rend="italic">Nature</hi>, 20 September [1873]</ref>.</note>
                
            </div>
        
